  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_297559506" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/297559506" />
    <a title="Stefanie Price" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/274632-stefanie-price"><img alt="Stefanie Price" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1327320900p2/274632.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/297559506?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stefanie Price" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stefanie Price" href="/user/show/274632-stefanie-price">Stefanie Price</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer297559506" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8091747495957983552">James Frey is my favourite writer by quite a margin. I wanted this book to be great. Better than great - I wanted it to fill the hole that an absence of Frey novels in recent years has created. <br/><br/>It started so promisingly, the premise was fantastic and the method of telling the story of a modern day Messiah through the eyes of those who came into contact with him gave the narrative texture and colour. Particularly wonderfully Frey-like were the accents and individual voices that jumped out of the </span>
  <span id="freeText8091747495957983552" style="display:none">James Frey is my favourite writer by quite a margin. I wanted this book to be great. Better than great - I wanted it to fill the hole that an absence of Frey novels in recent years has created. <br /><br />It started so promisingly, the premise was fantastic and the method of telling the story of a modern day Messiah through the eyes of those who came into contact with him gave the narrative texture and colour. Particularly wonderfully Frey-like were the accents and individual voices that jumped out of the text. He writes people and voice like nobody else. And true to form, Frey's own opinions about organised religion, government and god shines brightly. The main theme of the story is the pointlessness and evil of religion, and how that accompanied with gross consumer-driven capitalism and power-hungry governments are bringing about the end of days. A messiah is teaching about the beauty of life and love, and the evil of religion and government. The non-existence of a judgmental god, the equality between humans be they gay or straight, black or white...it all makes perfect sense and Frey rationalises brilliantly. I defy any religious person to read this and still be able to justify their beliefs. <br /><br />This caption in particular sticks in my memory: <br />"The Bible is a book. Books are for telling stories. They're not for denying people the right to live as they choose. Live by what you feel, and what feels right to you, not by what some book of stories tells you."<br /><br />My complaint is the repetitive narratives that occur throughout the book, which start to feel unnecessary and gratuitous. I am fine with reading about sex, but it began to feel like Frey was more into the 'fucking' than the story itself. Reading about it every 5 minutes grew dull, rather than exciting, and rather than communicating love, it just felt like Frey was trying to prove a point and getting off on his own subversiveness. <br /><br />He remains one of my favourite writers and I would definitely go to see a movie should one be made (and I think it easily could) of this film, although it would bomb in the States, where religion is much more prevalent than over here. If there were pickets around cinemas when the Darwin film was released, I think they'd be burning cinemas down if this were ever on general release! <br /><br />Unfortunately, the book does lose its momentum as it progresses, and the storytelling begins to echo itself to rather monotonous effect. And the people affected by their contact with the messiah's behaviour starts to seem a little dronelike and less impressive...perhaps this is just me, but something in the telling lost its power for me, despite being exactly in line with my own belief system. <br /><br />Nevertheless, this was an interesting and provocative read. I will be recommending it to others. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8091747495957983552" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


