    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_148664509" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/148664509" />
    <a title="Annette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4991550-annette"><img alt="Annette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298145105p2/4991550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/148664509?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Annette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Annette" href="/user/show/4991550-annette">Annette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Nook 2940012509956" href="/book/show/11198298-the-final-testament-of-the-holy-bible">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer148664509" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10582512500544703870">This book is the story of the messiah returning to earth told from the viewpoints of the people he affected while here. It is set in modern day New York. The messiah, Ben, basically rips apart modern day religion and politics. He tells people that the closest thing you&apos;ll get to God is an orgasm and that the Bible, Torah, and all other religious books are fiction. He does some of the typical messiah-type things like healing people and loving everyone, but he does a lot of non-typical things, too</span>
  <span id="freeText10582512500544703870" style="display:none">This book is the story of the messiah returning to earth told from the viewpoints of the people he affected while here. It is set in modern day New York. The messiah, Ben, basically rips apart modern day religion and politics. He tells people that the closest thing you'll get to God is an orgasm and that the Bible, Torah, and all other religious books are fiction. He does some of the typical messiah-type things like healing people and loving everyone, but he does a lot of non-typical things, too. He says that there is a God, but that he doesn't really care about us, he doesn't influence our lives in any way. That there is no afterlife, that we have this one life to live.<br /><br />I like to think that if the messiah were to come back, he would be exactly like Ben. Unfortunately, the world would probably treat him exactly like in this book with anger, misunderstanding, and hatred. <br /><br />One of my favorite passages:<br />"Faith is what you use to oppress, to deny, to justify, to judge in the name of God. Faith is what has been used as a means to rationalize more evil in this world than anything in history. If there were a Devil, faith would be his greatest invention. Get people to believe in that which does not exist, and have them use that belief to destroy everything of value in the world. Get them to buy into an idea of something false, and use that idea to create conflict, violence, and death. If you opened your eyes, you would see that the end is coming, that our world is going to end. And it is coming, and it is going to end, because of faith......<br />....There is hate, aggression, pride, a lack of love and patience, a lack of understanding, and there are weapons, weapons that can end it all, weapons that can kill millions of people in a second, and there are men, leaders of nations, who are willing to use them. Apocalypse will happen because of man, not because of a nonexistent God."<br /><br /><br />Religious people won't like this book, even though they could learn a lot from it. I thought it was great. The only reason I didn't give it 5 stars was because it got a little repetitive in the middle of the book. It seems like 3 or 4 people tell very similar stories about their interaction with Ben and it gets a little boring, but it picks back up after. It was an interesting viewpoint and one I enjoyed reading. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10582512500544703870" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


